Max Shift sets the possible maximum flexibility. Standard 1.15
Base Shift sets the starting flexibility. Standard 0.50

Low Shift: More controlled and potentially cleaner images with less risk of noise, but possibly less detail and sharpness.

nodes.title: Info
widgets_values:
All of these model corrections can improve or drastically worsen your images. This depends on the control point used. Therefore, I cannot make a general recommendation.

This also applies to KohyaDeepShrink and AutomaticCFG, which can further speed up your workflow. For example, the popular juggernoutXL X" model has major problems with KohyaDeepShrink. 

FreeU explaint by comfyanonymous:

b1 and b2 multiply half of the intermediate values coming from the previous blocks of the unet. b1 are for the intermediates in the lowest blocks and b2 is for the intermediates in the mid output blocks.

s1 and s2 scale the intermediate values coming from the input blocks that are concatenated to the ones from the previous block. Those intermediates are closer to the input of the unet so are less influenced by it.

Basically what you are doing is adjusting how much the deep layers of the unet have influence over the final image which is what increasing b1 and b2 and decreasing s1 and s2 does.

nodes.title: Behind it is noodle salad
widgets_values:
We will place information here to hide the confusion a little. ;-)

Temperature settings node is back:  Info from the developer: Images are burnt more than my pizza when coding: Temperature too low
Pictures are blurry, as if I had taken off my glasses: temperature too high.
https://github.com/Extraltodeus/Stable-Diffusion-temperature-settings

We have installed the LatentGarbageCollector node from the ntdviet/comfyui-ext CustomNodes on a trial basis to empty the VRAM. We do not know exactly how well this works. The attempt to remove the models that we use in the Reactor Node for face swap from the VRAM in order to be able to continue working with our 8GB VRM card at normal speed unfortunately did not work. We believe that these nodes have a positive effect on the speed of the entire workflow. However, you can also simply remove them (the light yellow ones) if you have more VRAM available.

We use the _MOHAWK_v2.0 model from Prof. Aurety, which you can download or try out here:
https://civitai.com/models/144952?modelVersionId=286100

Depending on the model, CFG, Steps, Sampler and Scheduler must be selected. Pony, Flux, Turbo, Lightning,... require precise settings for the respective model

Infos to Flux:
CFG is automatically set to 1
Flux schnell Model need 4 Steps

You should have at least 32 GB RAM
and 12 GB VRAM
Less is also possible but, leads to crashes or very long generation times.
